textMap.PRIMARY: It is understood that the aim of the Japanese was to oust Western Imperialist Powers from East and South East Asia, establishing what came to be known as the Greater East Asian Co-Prosperity Sphere. Wherever they emerged victorious, they put local governments in charge and controlled them from behind the scenes. However, they were not benign masters - (mass) killings of local people were not unheard of, although they did not systematically exercise 'ethnic cleansing' in the areas they controlled. In Japan's formal colonies, Korea and Taiwan, people were forced to adopt Japanese names and observe Japanese religious customs, including worshiping the Emperor. Refusal to obey those rules could easily lead to arrest and a death sentence. The Kempeitai played a key role in the eradication of resistance movements. The Japanese government also actively encouraged Japanese settlement on the Asian mainland in order to provide the Japanese homeland with food and other natural resources.
San Francisco's cable car system was designed in the late 1800's by Andrew Smith Hallidie.

"Solid State TV's" by present standards would be considered vintage television sets. In the 1960's, television technology was advancing from the use of vacuum tubing to solid state electronic circuit boards created entirely from solid materials.

Color television was introduced in the early fifties, but didn't become commonplace until later in the mid 1960's. However, in the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the technology was developed and rolled out by the Nazis much faster, meaning that people were watching the Fhrer in full color as the fifties began.

Wire-tapping has been used in law enforcement since as early as the 1890s. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," wire-tapping is commonly used on anyone of interest in the Japanese Pacific States.
When shooting on the back-lot set of Canon City, the local Burnaby, BC hills facing North had to be painted out and replaced with the Colorado Rockies.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," trade is strictly controlled across the borders of the Neutral Zone. A limited amount of essentials goods are traded in the zone at extremely poor exchange rates, while natural resources were being exported.

In "The Man in the High Castle," the Neutral Zone is a lawless "no-man's-land" that divides German and Japanese territories in America. Although both powers allow people to live in the zone, no formal system of governance or law enforcement is allowed to be in place. Both powers employ operatives in the zone in order to undermine any such organization forming.

The Nazis had a history of burning books. The German Student Union conducted a campaign to ceremonially burn books in Nazi Germany and Austria in the 1930s. The books targeted for burning were those viewed as being subversive or as representing ideologies opposed to Nazism. These included books written by Jewish, pacifist, classical liberal, anarchist, socialist, and communist authors, among others.

Playing cards with photos of 'most wanted' enemy leaders have historically been distributed to troops in wartime as an aid in identifying the target. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," The Marshal uses this same system to identify those that the Nazis have him hunting.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Crown Prince of Japan is 29 years old. He was raised and educated by private tutors in Tokyo before being evacuated during the war. Unusually for the imperial family, he was allowed to choose his own bride, yet always knew who he wanted to choose. His distant cousin had been on his mind as his future wife for some time; she was beautiful, kind and always put others before herself. He holds reservations about one day becoming Emperor and the huge responsibility bestowed on him. He worries that he is not strong enough to lead his people and could never step into his father's shoes. However, he feels a strong sense of duty to his people, the 'children' of Japan, and is determined to make the Pacific States prosper. He holds a modern view of Japan where he envisions the Americans and Japanese living harmoniously.

The Crown Princess, in the world of "The Man in the High Castle," is 28 years old. She was educated at a girls school in Tokyo before being betrothed to her distant cousin. Following this betrothal, she began a six year training program to develop the skills deemed necessary for a future empress. She played no part in choosing a husband, yet had been very fond of her distant cousin for some time, and secretly desired that he would choose her for his bride. She is dynamic and focused, wholeheartedly believing in her husband as a pillar of faith for their people. She also provides a clear vision for her husband and what they can achieve.
Those found accompanying the Crown Prince and Princess are part of the Royal Household. Among them are the Crown Prince's valet and the Crown Princess' lady in waiting.
This filming location is in New Westminster, BC.
The Crown Prince of Japan is performing a Shinto ritual of Tamagushi. Tamagushi is an offering made from an evergreen branch to pay formal worship to the gods.
The Shinto Head Priest is wearing an eboshi or "crow" hat. This type of headdress is worn by Shinto priests during ritualistic ceremonies.

The costume design of "The Man in The High Castle" Crown Prince and Princess was inspired by real life Crown Prince Akihito and Princess Michiko of the same era. Married in 1959, Prince Akihito and Princess Michiko ascended to the throne in 1989 when Akihito's father, Emperor Hirohito, died. The couple are Japan's current Emperor and Empress.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the bounty hunter known as 'The Marshal' collects the fingers of Jews that he kills as a way of tracking his bounty to be paid by the Nazis. In reality, during the Holocaust, bounty hunters were ordinary citizens in need of funds who would be given money by the Nazis in exchange for captured Jews. Sometimes these bounty hunters would travel hundreds of miles in pursuit of their targets.

The Nazis experimented extensively on prisoners of war, Jews, and other 'unwanted' during WWII for a number of reasons, including the intention of discovering a viable 'truth serum.' Lysergic Acid Diethylamide, more commonly known as LSD, was developed shortly after the war in Europe and brought to America. Even the USA was experimenting with viable 'truth serums' since the development of the Cold War; they quickly recognized the mind-altering potential of LSD and experimented with it extensively. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," it is the Germans who recognize the potential of LSD as a 'truth serum' and use it as part of their interrogation techniques.
The filming location where Joe and Juliana sink The Line Faced Man's body in the river is in North Vancouver, Canada.

The medal being presented to the Crown Prince and Princess is the Knights Cross of the German Order of Victory. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the German Order of Victory is a series of decorations given in recognition of valor or exemplary service to Germany and its allied nations. The Knight's Cross is the highest grade in the series and reserved for top ranking military officers, government officials, and heads of state.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Nazis are displaying respect and sensitivity to the Japanese culture by applying the practice of Feng Shui in the arrangement of the furniture during the Crown Prince and Princess' visit to the Nazi Embassy. An extensive amount of research and consultation on the part of "The Man in the High Castle" Art Department went into understanding how Japanese royals are positioned in public settings. Both modern and historical references indicated the Emperor and Empress would be seated in front of a royal screen panel.

Throughout most of Japanese history, the Japanese Emperor was merely a figurehead. He was seen as a descendant of the Sun Goddess Amaterasu, the highest deity in the Japanese pantheon. Japanese ideology in the 1930's and during the Second World War centered around the Emperor as Divine Father of the Japanese people, and every order was executed in his name. The sense of Japanese superiority over other Asian countries manifested itself through 'divine ancestry,' and through never having been colonized by a Western power. The Crown Prince is the Emperor-in-Waiting.

Tea ceremonies in Japan are about much more than just drinking tea - they are about harmony, respect, and purity. They are simple yet meticulously planned, the art of which can take years to master. Tea is an important part of Japanese culture and was introduced from China in the 700's.
This mine shaft was filmed in Britannia, BC.
